Answer: Step 1: Condense 6-dimethylamino-1-naphthylamine with diethyl ethoxymethylenemalonate to form the corresponding anilinomethylenemalonate (Gould-Jacobs enamine) intermediate. | Step 2: Thermally cyclize this intermediate (e.g. in diphenyl ether) to give ethyl 7-dimethylaminobenzo[h]quinoline-4-one-3-carboxylate. | Step 3: Hydrolyze the ester, then decarboxylate, to obtain 7-dimethylaminobenzo[h]quinolin-4(1H)-one. | Step 4: In parallel, N-benzylate 4-piperidone to give N-benzyl-4-piperidone. | Step 5: Reduce the ketone to N-benzyl-4-piperidinol, then convert the alcohol to a leaving-group derivative (4-chloro, 4-bromo, mesylate, or tosylate) to make the N-benzyl-4-substituted piperidine electrophile. | Step 6: Deprotonate 7-dimethylaminobenzo[h]quinolin-4(1H)-one with NaH, K2CO3, or Cs2CO3 and perform N-alkylation with the activated N-benzylpiperidine derivative to furnish the exact target CN(C)c1ccc2ccc(=O)n(C3CCN(Cc4ccccc4)CC3)c2c1.

